om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Stocks keep going up</h2><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A model of corp=
orate finance <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/2429=
3736.260983/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTU=
tMDMtMjQvcHJpdmF0ZS1jb21wYW5pZXMtd2lsbC10YWtlLW1vbmV5LXB1YmxpYy1jb21wYW5pZX=
MtZG9uLXQtd2FudA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBf1f4f8c9" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" =
itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !imp=
ortant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bott=
om-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> that I like</a> and find helpful=
 goes like this:</p><ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40=
px; margin: 16px 0;">=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">A company is foun=
ded to do a thing.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">It raises money=
 from investors to do the thing.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">I=
t spends the money to=C2=A0do the thing.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom:=
 5px;">It does the thing profitably, which generates money.</li>=09<li styl=
e=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">It gives some of the money that it earned from do=
ing the thing back to investors, pays some of the money to its founders and=
 managers as compensation for their entrepreneurial vision, and invests som=
e of the money in doing even more of the thing.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-=
bottom: 5px;">Eventually the thing stops being profitable and the company g=
oes away.</li></ol><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I have phrased it as simply=
 and stupidly as possible to make it sound inevitable and obvious, but of c=
ourse it isn=E2=80=99t; this is by no means the only model of corporate fin=
ance. The main alternative is the same through step 4, then=C2=A0branches o=
ff in step 5:</p><ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px;=
 margin: 16px 0;">=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Found company.</li>=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Raise money.</li>=09<li style=3D"margi=
n-bottom: 5px;">Do thing.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Make mon=
ey.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The company pays some of the m=
oney to its founders and managers as compensation for their entrepreneurial=
 vision, invests some of the money in doing even more of the thing, and inv=
ests the rest of the money in <em>finding new things to do</em>.</li>=09<li=
 style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Eventually the original thing stops being pr=
ofitable but the company is doing new profitable things instead, which gene=
rate more money.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Go to step 5.</li=
></ol><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">My simple model=C2=A0terminates in step =
6; this one has an infinite loop: The company=C2=A0uses the profits from th=
e thing it does now to fund the next thing, and the profits from that fund =
the=C2=A0<em>next=C2=A0</em>thing, etc.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0=
;">Obviously most real companies look like some combination of these models=
. Real companies that make money use it to invest in research and developme=
nt and new products and new markets and so forth. But also real companies i=
n secularly declining industries often =E2=80=A6=C2=A0decline. If you run a=
 sprocket factory it is hard to transition to making social-media apps. A c=
ompany will have some expertise, some set of things it is good at, and if t=
hose things are no longer valuable, the best thing for it to do might be to=
 give its profits back to its investors and quietly go away. And then the i=
nvestors could invest the money in some=C2=A0<em>new=C2=A0</em>startup that=
 was purpose-built to do a new thing, that has its own expertise in doing t=
hings that are now valuable.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Or not. A comp=
any will also have some set of social relationships and office space and le=
tterhead and chairs and stuff, and it might be wasteful for the company to =
just go away while=C2=A0some other new company =E2=80=94=C2=A0with some new=
, currently more valuable expertise =E2=80=94 has to build up those things =
all over again. Maybe the old company should pivot into doing the new thing=
, or maybe it should acquire the new company to give it the new-thing exper=
tise, etc. These are obviously fact-dependent questions. Some companies can=
 do new things or integrate acquisitions well; others can gracefully declin=
e.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">For most of the time that I have been wr=
iting about finance, a basic theme of public-market corporate finance was w=
hat you might call =E2=80=9Cdiscipline.=E2=80=9D Public companies did thing=
s, and made money, and gave a fair amount of the money back to shareholders=
. Conglomeration and =E2=80=9Cempire-building=E2=80=9D were viewed as bad; =
stock buybacks were good. =E2=80=9CPeople are worried about stock buybacks,=
=E2=80=9D I wrote as a recurring bit: Investors and corporate executives br=
oadly=C2=A0embraced the doctrine that if a company made money, it should re=
turn the money to investors to put into the next thing, rather than trying =
to find the next thing itself. This was=C2=A0a view that many politicians a=
nd journalists found infuriating (shouldn=E2=80=99t companies be trying to =
find the next thing themselves? shouldn=E2=80=99t America be innovating?), =
but it=C2=A0struck me as sort of conventional corporate finance. It was mos=
tly the first model of corporate finance, though, a model in which companie=
s stick to the thing they=E2=80=99re good at rather than noodling around tr=
ying to find something new.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Of course a few=
 wildly successful=C2=A0companies did devote lots of money to moonshots, bu=
t these companies seemed exceptional and their freedom was much remarked on=
. Alphabet Inc., Amazon.com Inc., perhaps Facebook Inc., perhaps Tesla Inc.=
=C2=A0were the famous examples; all of them had made enough money for inves=
tors through innovation that they were given a free hand to try for more. A=
lso Alphabet and Facebook have multi-class stock that insulates their found=
ers from outside shareholder pressure, and=C2=A0<em>that=C2=A0</em>innovati=
on was much copied by other tech companies, because other founder-CEOs also=
 wanted that sort of freedom from market pressure and capital discipline. T=
he assumption was that public markets were =E2=80=9Cshort-termist,=E2=80=9D=
 meaning something like =E2=80=9Cunwilling to finance speculative projects =
that don=E2=80=99t have a clear fit with the company=E2=80=99s current busi=
ness or a clear path to profitability,=E2=80=9D and companies that went pub=
lic had to carefully guard their freedom.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">M=
eanwhile venture capitalists funded all sorts of wild money-losing stuff ho=
ping that some of it would work. But that was in private markets, which wer=
e weird and insulated from disciplinary measures like activist hedge funds =
and short sellers. Public markets were about short-termism and capital disc=
ipline.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I am trying to describe how the wor=
ld felt like two or three years ago because it feels very different now. He=
re for instance is a Bloomberg article titled =E2=80=9C<a href=3D"https://l=
ink.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24293736.260983/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb2=
1iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDYtMjcvcmVjb3JkLXN0b2NrLXNhbGVzLWZyb=
20tbW9uZXktbG9zaW5nLWZpcm1zLXJpbmctdGhlLWFsYXJtLWJlbGxz/607f07ceef4b8524a31=
9a23cB357b87e5" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"col=
or: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bo=
rder-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #=
ccc;">Record Stock Sales From Money-Losing Firms Ring the Alarm Bells</a>=
=E2=80=9D:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you think a rush =
by companies to sell their shares is a bad omen for the market, imagine a s=
cenario where most of the sales come from firms that don=E2=80=99t make mon=
ey.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It=E2=80=99s happening now. Since the e=
nd of March, almost 100 unprofitable U.S. companies, including GameStop Cor=
p. and AMC Entertainment Holdings Inc., have raised money through secondary=
 offerings, twice as many as coming from profitable firms, according to dat=
a compiled by Bloomberg. =E2=80=A6</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">During t=
he past 12 months, almost 750 money-losing firms have sold shares in the se=
condary market, exceeding those that make profits by the biggest margin sin=
ce at least 1982, data compiled by Sundial Capital Research show.</p><p sty=
le=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CThat perhaps points to companies getting gr=
eedy,=E2=80=9D said Mike Bailey, director of research at FBB Capital Partne=
rs. =E2=80=9CAnytime you have a bunch of selling by desperate companies, th=
at could be a signal we=E2=80=99re closer to a top than a cyclical bottom.=
=E2=80=9D</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One way to read that=
 story is that AMC and GameStop are currently in businesses that are bad, a=
s evidenced by the fact that they lose money. They would like to get into b=
usinesses that are good, in different ways. (AMC by buying up theaters to d=
ouble down on its current business, as far as I can tell; GameStop by myste=
riously transforming into some sort of tech company.) Three years ago that =
was a hard sell: It was not easy for a public company to go to investors an=
d say =E2=80=9Chey it turns out that the business we are in loses money, we=
 would like to get into a different business, would you finance that?=E2=80=
=9D Now =E2=80=A6=C2=A0I am not sure it=E2=80=99s easy, but it=E2=80=99s ce=
rtainly easier.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One way for GameStop to piv=
ot might be=C2=A0to use all the money it can raise to go <em>buy=C2=A0</em>=
a tech company. People have pointed out that it is almost an informal=C2=A0=
SPAC, a special purpose acquisition company, in that it has <a href=3D"http=
s://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24293736.260983/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuY=
mxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDYtMjIvZ2FtZXN0b3AtanVtcHMtYWZ0=
ZXItcmFpc2luZy0xLTEtYmlsbGlvbi1pbi1zdG9jay1zYWxlLXByb2dyYW0/607f07ceef4b852=
4a319a23cB222c5552" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D=
"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px=
; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-colo=
r: #ccc;"> raised a billion dollars</a> with no clear use of proceeds and c=
an now, if it wants, use that money to buy into a new business.=C2=A0GameSt=
op has raised so much money that its current expertise in mall-based video-=
game retail (a declining industry!) doesn=E2=80=99t matter; it can hire all=
-new expertise in the form of <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusines=
s.com/click/24293736.260983/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2F=
ydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDYtMTAvbWF5YmUtZ2FtZXN0b3AtaXMtZ29vZC1ub3c/607f07ceef4b85=
24a319a23cBf7d0f982" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;"> an executive team poached from Amazon</a>, and then go out an=
d acquire a not-at-all-mall-based business, and just become a new company. =
Because shareholders will cheerfully fund it.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: =
16px 0;">Of course SPACs themselves =E2=80=94=C2=A0special purpose acquisit=
ion companies, in which successful financial or operating executives raise =
pools of money to buy whatever business they like =E2=80=94=C2=A0are a simi=
lar story. If you=E2=80=99ve had=C2=A0success running some business, the pu=
blic markets are absolutely clamoring to trust you to run some other unrela=
ted business. (Or were, anyway, earlier this year.) And =E2=80=9CThe IPO Ma=
rket Has Never Been Hotter Than It Is Right Now=E2=80=9D is <a href=3D"http=
s://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24293736.260983/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuY=
mxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDYtMjcvdGhlLWdsb2JhbC1pcG8tbWFy=
a2V0LWhhcy1uZXZlci1iZWVuLWhvdHRlci10aGFuLWl0LWlzLXJpZ2h0LW5vdw/607f07ceef4b=
