idth: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgr=
ound-color: #ccc;"> simpler or better</a>. For instance: What if instead of=
 some weird manipulable auction to determine CDS recovery, every CDS contra=
ct just paid out a fixed amount? And I say: Sure, I guess that would be fin=
e, but it would make CDS=C2=A0<em>less useful=C2=A0</em>as a hedge to actua=
l bonds. It would pay out =E2=80=9Ctoo much=E2=80=9D on a default =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0$100 of CDS would pay out $100, which is more than you'd lose on $100=
 of defaulted bonds (which get some recovery) =E2=80=94=C2=A0which means th=
at you=E2=80=99d have to carefully size and perhaps dynamically modify your=
 CDS position as a hedge to your bond position. If you want a derivative to=
 work as a hedge for an underlying thing =E2=80=94 as opposed to a simple y=
es/no bet =E2=80=94=C2=A0then it will have to be a bit complicated.</p><p s=
tyle=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Similarly, if you wanted to bet that U.S. Treasury=
 yields would go up or down, you might read <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bl=
oombergbusiness.com/click/24293736.260983/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvb=
