a> (and a related <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/=
24293736.260983/aHR0cHM6Ly9jb3JwZ292Lmxhdy5oYXJ2YXJkLmVkdS8yMDIxLzA2LzI3L3B=
oYW50b20tb2YtdGhlLW9wZXJhLWV0Zi1zaG9ydGluZy1hbmQtc2hhcmVob2xkZXItdm90aW5nLw=
/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBa9a53ee0" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"ite=
mscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-b=
ottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid;=
 background-color: #ccc;">blog post</a>) titled =E2=80=9CPhantom of the Ope=
ra: ETF Shorting and Shareholder Voting,=E2=80=9D by=C2=A0Richard B. Evans,=
 O=C4=9Fuzhan Karaka=C5=9F, Rabih Moussawi and Michael Young, arguing that =
this dynamic means =E2=80=9Cthat phantom shares, stemming from short-sellin=
g of ETF shares (for ETF market making, directional, or hedging purposes), =
lead to sidelined votes during the proxy voting process.=E2=80=9D From the =
blog post:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">To be clear, our evi=
dence does not suggest that ETF sponsors (e.g., BlackRock, State Street, Va=
nguard) do not vote the underlying shares in their ETF portfolios. Instead,=
 (as a presumably unintended consequence of ETF security design) we show th=
at when ETF shares are sold short, constituent companies=E2=80=99 shares th=
at are not held by the ETF sponsor and would otherwise be voted, are held e=
xplicitly or effectively as collateral, and as a result, the holder general=
ly abstains from proxy voting. This abstention effectively decouples the ca=
sh flow rights from the voting rights of the corresponding ETF share. We re=
fer to these as =E2=80=9Cphantom ETF shares=E2=80=9D, and the underlying sh=
ares held as collateral as =E2=80=9Cphantom shares=E2=80=9D. We demonstrate=
 that these phantom shares are associated with decreased proxy voting and i=
ncreased broker non-votes, voting premium, and value-reducing acquisitions.=
</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">When you buy shares of an ind=
ex fund, the index fund company goes out and buys shares of the stocks in t=
he underlying index. You own some proportional share of the underlying stoc=
ks; $100 of your money represents something close to $100 of underlying sto=
cks. (Actually about $98, because the index fund keeps a little cash on han=
d for redemptions.)=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">When you buy shar=
es of an exchange-traded fund, you are just buying them in the market, not =
from the ETF company. Some of the shares come from the ETF company; others =
come from short sellers.=C2=A0If you buy =E2=80=9Clong=E2=80=9D shares =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0that is, shares that came from the ETF company =E2=80=94=C2=A0t=
hen $100 of your money represents something close to $100 of the underlying=
 stocks. (Probably pretty close to $100, since stock index ETFs generally d=
on=E2=80=99t need cash to pay redemptions.) If you buy =E2=80=9Cshort=E2=80=
=9D shares =E2=80=94=C2=A0that is, shares that come from someone shorting t=
he ETF =E2=80=94=C2=A0then it doesn=E2=80=99t. Your $100 represents, effect=
ively, a bet with the short seller. The short seller has to borrow ETF shar=
es to deliver to you, and it has to deliver collateral to its broker to get=
 those shares. The collateral might be cash or it might be the underlying b=
asket of stocks. If it=E2=80=99s cash, then no one owns the underlying bask=
et of stocks and your money does not represent any votes. If it=E2=80=99s s=
tock, then the short seller owns the underlying basket and delivers them to=
 the broker for collateral; the broker probably doesn=E2=80=99t vote them. =
Either way, no one is voting the shares that you sort of =E2=80=9Cown,=E2=
=80=9D indirectly, through your purchase of ETF shares. From the paper:</p>=
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The phantom ETF share, however, is=
 backed by the collateral held by the securities lender. If this collateral=
 does not correspond to the ETF=E2=80=99s underlying securities (e.g., cash=
 plus a S&amp;P 500 futures overlay), then it would not be associated with =
any proxy voting. For ETFs, however, this collateral may consist of the und=
erlying securities (e.g., the portfolio of S&amp;P 500 securities). In cont=
rast to the underlying shares backing the original share and both held and =
voted by the ETF sponsor, these securities are held by the broker/securitie=
s lender, and may not be voted except for =E2=80=98routine=E2=80=99 matters=
 due to the limitations on broker voting. Effectively, these underlying sha=
res have been sidelined from the voting process due to their status as coll=
ateral.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">They estimate that abo=
ut 14% of S&amp;P 500 index ETF shares=C2=A0are shorted. This means that if=
 you put $100 into an S&amp;P 500 index ETF, you are getting $100 of econom=
ic exposure to the stocks in the index, but only $86 worth of voting rights=
. Of course you weren=E2=80=99t voting anyway =E2=80=94=C2=A0the ETF compan=
y was =E2=80=94=C2=A0and the fact that you=E2=80=99re buying an index ETF s=
uggests you might not care that much about the vote. We talk from time to t=
ime about arguments that index funds <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomberg=
business.com/click/24293736.260983/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGlu=
